\f2  (bush) \'96 To be ashamed, dismayed, confounded.\
	\'95	Physical Root: To shrink back, cover oneself.\
	\'95	Genesis 3:7: \'93Then the eyes of both of them were opened, and they knew they were naked; and they sewed fig leaves together.\'94\
	\'95	
\f3 \uc0\u1499 \u1464 \u1468 \u1500 \u1460 \u1497 \u1501 
\f2  (kalim) \'96 Disgrace, humiliation.\
	\'95	Physical Root: The public exposure of vulnerability.\
	\'95	Jeremiah 20:11: \'93The Lord is with me\'85 my persecutors will stumble and will not prevail; they will be greatly ashamed.\'94\
\
Key Insight:\
	\'95	Shame is internal exposure (bush) and external disgrace (kalim).\
	\'95	Shame is relational: it arises from disconnection from God, self, and others.\
\
II. The Spirit of the Accuser: Ha-Satan in the Old Testament\
\
Hebrew: 
\f3 \uc0\u1513 \u1464 \u1474 \u1496 \u1464 \u1503 
\f2  (Satan) \'96 Adversary, accuser.\
	\'95	Physical Root: To obstruct or oppose as a legal challenger.\
\
Primary Text:\
	\'95	Job 1:6-11: \'93The Accuser came among them\'85 \'91Does Job fear God for nothing?\'92\'94\
	\'95	Zechariah 3:1: \'93Then he showed me Joshua the high priest\'85 and Satan standing at his right hand to accuse him.\'94\
\
Key Insight:\
	\'95	The Accuser distorts truth by focusing on guilt without grace.\
	\'95	The Accuser\'92s voice echoes through legalism, fear, and self-condemnation.\
\
