	\'95	Revelation 12:10: \'93The accuser of our brothers has been cast down.\'94\
\
The Accuser\'92s Strategy in the Gospels\
	1.	False Legalism (Pharisees)\
	\'95	Luke 11:53-54: The Pharisees lay accusations against Jesus for His healing.\
	2.	Public Shame (Adulterous Woman)\
	\'95	John 8:3-11: The Pharisees use public disgrace to condemn the woman caught in adultery.\
	3.	Twisting Truth (Satan\'92s Temptation)\
	\'95	Matthew 4:1-11: The Accuser distorts Scripture in the wilderness to challenge Christ\'92s identity.\
\
IV. Shame as a Weapon of the Accuser\
\
The Psychological Effect of Shame:\
	\'95	Shame isolates: It drives the soul to hide (Gen 3:10).\
	\'95	Shame distorts: It twists identity, reducing the person to their failure.\
	\'95	Shame paralyzes: It cripples action, leaving the soul inward-focused.\
\
V. The Cross of Christ as the End of Shame\
\
Greek: 
\f3 \uc0\u945 \u953 \u963 \u967 \u965 \u957 \u951 
\f2  (aischyn\uc0\u275 ) \'96 Shame, disgrace.\
	\'95	Physical Root: To be exposed to scorn.\
\
Hebrews 12:2:\
\'93Looking unto Jesus, the author and finisher of our faith, who for the joy set before Him endured the cross, despising the shame.\'94\
\
How Christ Defeats Shame and the Accuser:\
	1.	He Endured Shame on Our Behalf:\
	\'95	The public crucifixion exposed Jesus naked and humiliated (Mark 15:24).\
	\'95	He bore the shame we deserved, fulfilling Isaiah\'92s prophecy (Isa. 53:5).\
	2.	He Silences the Accuser:\
	\'95	Revelation 12:11: \'93They overcame him by the blood of the Lamb and the word of their testimony.\'94\
	\'95	Christ\'92s blood removes the basis for accusation.\
	3.	He Restores Our Honor:\
	\'95	Isaiah 61:7: \'93Instead of shame, you shall have double honor.\'94\
	\'95	We are clothed in righteousness (2 Cor. 5:21).\
\
VI. Overcoming Shame in the Christian Life\
\
1. Identify the Accuser\'92s Voice:\
	\'95	Does it condemn without hope?\
	\'95	Does it isolate you from the body of Christ?\
\
2. Confront with the Gospel:\
	\'95	The Accuser\'92s power is broken by the blood of Christ.\
	\'95	Romans 8:1: \'93There is now no condemnation for those in Christ Jesus.\'94\
\
3. Replace Shame with Honor:\
	\'95	Ephesians 1:6: \'93He made us accepted in the Beloved.\'94\
	\'95	Biblical forgiveness restores identity, not just status.\
\
VII. The Theological Contrast: Biblical Shame vs. Pagan Shame\
\
Biblical Shame:\
	\'95	Temporary: Designed to lead to repentance (2 Cor. 7:10).\
	\'95	God-Directed: Focused on restoration and holiness.\
	\'95	Contextual: Tied to covenant faithfulness.\
\
Pagan Shame (The Accuser\'92s Design):\
	\'95	Permanent: Seeks to define the whole person by failure.\
	\'95	Self-Directed: Focused on self-punishment and despair.\
	\'95	Honor-Culture Based: Tied to reputation and public opinion.\
\
VIII. The Church as the Healing Community Against Shame\
\
The ecclesia is called to be a place where shame dies and grace reigns:\
	\'95	Confession Without Condemnation:\
	\'95	James 5:16: \'93Confess your sins to one another that you may be healed.\'94\
	\'95	Preaching the Finished Work of Christ:\
	\'95	1 John 2:1: \'93If anyone sins, we have an Advocate with the Father.\'94\
	\'95	Restoration, Not Rejection:\
	\'95	Galatians 6:1: \'93Restore such a one in a spirit of gentleness.\'94\
\
IX. Conclusion: Christ is Our Honor\
\
The spirit of the accuser thrives on shame, but Christ\'92s victory silences it forever.\
	\'95	Satan condemns; Christ justifies.\
	\'95	Shame binds; Christ liberates.\
	\'95	The Accuser speaks lies; Christ speaks truth.\
\
As you walk in Christ:\
	\'95	Reject false shame.\
	\'95	Speak grace over others.\
	\'95	Rest in the honor Christ has restored.\
